541 /**
542 Read-write lock protecting this lock context.
543
544 @note The fact that we use read-write lock prefers readers here is
545 important as deadlock detector won't work correctly otherwise.
546
547 For example, imagine that we have following waiters graph:
548
549 ctxA -> obj1 -> ctxB -> obj1 -|
550 ^ |
551 |----------------------------|
552
553 and both ctxA and ctxB start deadlock detection process:
554
555 ctxA read-locks obj1 ctxB read-locks obj2
556 ctxA goes deeper ctxB goes deeper
557
558 Now ctxC comes in who wants to start waiting on obj1, also
559 ctxD comes in who wants to start waiting on obj2.
560
561 ctxC tries to write-lock obj1 ctxD tries to write-lock obj2
562 ctxC is blocked ctxD is blocked
563
564 Now ctxA and ctxB resume their search:
565
566 ctxA tries to read-lock obj2 ctxB tries to read-lock obj1
567
568 If m_rwlock prefers writes (or fair) both ctxA and ctxB would be
569 blocked because of pending write locks from ctxD and ctxC
570 correspondingly. Thus we will get a deadlock in deadlock detector.
571 If m_wrlock prefers readers (actually ignoring pending writers is
572 enough) ctxA and ctxB will continue and no deadlock will occur.
573 */

694 /**
695 4659682 @returns "Fast path" increment for request for "unobtrusive" type
696 of lock, 0 - if it is request for "obtrusive" type of
697 lock.
698
699 @note We split all lock types for each of MDL namespaces
700 in two sets:
701
702 A) "unobtrusive" lock types
703 1) Each type from this set should be compatible with all other
704 types from the set (including itself).
705 2) These types should be common for DML operations
706
707 Our goal is to optimize acquisition and release of locks of this
708 type by avoiding complex checks and manipulations on m_waiting/
709 m_granted bitmaps/lists. We replace them with a check of and
710 increment/decrement of integer counters.
711 We call the latter type of acquisition/release "fast path".
712 Use of "fast path" reduces the size of critical section associated
713 with MDL_lock::m_rwlock lock in the common case and thus increases
714 scalability.
715
716 The amount by which acquisition/release of specific type
717 "unobtrusive" lock increases/decreases packed counter in
718 MDL_lock::m_fast_path_state is returned by this function.

722 some other types of locks or with itself.

726 m_waiting/m_granted bitmaps/lists, i.e. we have to use "slow path"
727 for them. Moreover in the presence of active/pending locks from
728 "obtrusive" set we have to acquire using "slow path" even locks of
